docs.title: 311_service_requests
docs.text:
Last modified at

2024-03-07

Created at

2017-05-18

Nb Rows

1,803,085

Size

446.87 MB

Description

No description

Open in BigQuery 🡒

Columns

Column Type Description unique_key STRING The service request tracking number. complaint_description STRING Service request type source STRING Contact method Service request was received from. Mass entry requests are submitted by dept. in groups after work is completed. status STRING Service request status. Duplicate statuses indicate that issue had previously been reported recently. status_change_date TIMESTAMP Date of last Service request status change. Status changes occur when service request moves from one status to another. I.E. new to open, open to closed. created_date TIMESTAMP Date Service request was created. last_update_date TIMESTAMP Date Service request was updated. Last date Service request received updates. Updates may include creation, status changes, or changes to data in Service request. close_date TIMESTAMP Date Service request was closed. incident_address STRING Service location of Service request. street_number STRING Parsed location information. Street number. street_name STRING Parsed location information. Street name. city STRING Parsed location information. City. incident_zip INT64 Parsed location information. Zip code. county STRING Parsed location information. County. state_plane_x_coordinate STRING State plane X coordinate. state_plane_y_coordinate FLOAT64 State plane Y coordinate. latitude FLOAT64 Service request location latitude coordinate. longitude FLOAT64 Service request location longitude coordinate. location STRING Service request location latitude and longitude coordinates. council_district_code INT64 Council district corresponding to Service request location. Locations outside of the City of Austin jurisdiction will not have a council district. map_page STRING Service request location corresponding map page. map_tile STRING Service request location corresponding map tile.

docs.text:

Overview: This dataset includes economic statistics on inflation, prices, unemployment, and pay & benefits provided by the Bureau of Labor Statistics (BLS).

Update frequency: Monthly

Dataset source: U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics

Terms of use: This dataset is publicly available for anyone to use under the following terms provided by the Dataset Source - http://www.data.gov/privacy-policy#data_policy - and is provided "AS IS" without any warranty, express or implied, from Google. Google disclaims all liability for any damages, direct or indirect, resulting from the use of the dataset.

See the GCP Marketplace listing for more details and sample queries: https://console.cloud.google.com/marketplace/details/bls-public-data/bureau-of-labor-statistics

docs.title: chicago_crime
docs.text:
Description

This dataset reflects reported incidents of crime (with the exception of murders where data exists for each victim) that occurred in the City of Chicago from 2001 to present, minus the most recent seven days. Data is extracted from the Chicago Police Department's CLEAR (Citizen Law Enforcement Analysis and Reporting) system. In order to protect the privacy of crime victims, addresses are shown at the block level only and specific locations are not identified. This data includes unverified reports supplied to the Police Department. The preliminary crime classifications may be changed at a later date based upon additional investigation and there is always the possibility of mechanical or human error. Therefore, the Chicago Police Department does not guarantee (either expressed or implied) the accuracy, completeness, timeliness, or correct sequencing of the information and the information should not be used for comparison purposes over time.

Dataset Source: City of Chicago

Category: Chicago, Public Safety

Use: This dataset is publicly available for anyone to use under the following terms provided by the Dataset Source —https://data.cityofchicago.org — and is provided "AS IS" without any warranty, express or implied, from Google. Google disclaims all liability for any damages, direct or indirect, resulting from the use of the dataset.

Update Frequency: Daily

docs.title: covid19_google_mobility
docs.text:
Description

UPDATE: The Community Mobility Reports are no longer being updated as of October 15, 2022. All historical data will remain publicly available for research purposes.

Terms of use In order to download or use the data or reports, you must agree to the Google Terms of Service: https://policies.google.com/terms

Description This dataset aims to provide insights into what has changed in response to policies aimed at combating COVID-19. It reports movement trends over time by geography, across different categories of places such as retail and recreation, groceries and pharmacies, parks, transit stations, workplaces, and residential.

This dataset is intended to help remediate the impact of COVID-19. It shouldn’t be used for medical diagnostic, prognostic, or treatment purposes. It also isn’t intended to be used for guidance on personal travel plans.

To learn more about the dataset, the place categories, and how we calculate these trends and preserve privacy, do the following:

• Visit the help center: https://support.google.com/covid19-mobility.

• Or, read the dataset documentation: https://www.google.com/covid19/mobility/data_documentation.html.

Columns

Column Type Description country_region_code STRING 2 letter alpha code for the country/region in which changes are measured relative to the baseline. These values correspond with the ISO 3166-1 alpha-2 codes country_region STRING The country/region in which changes are measured relative to the baseline sub_region_1 STRING First geographic sub-region in which the data is aggregated. This varies by country/region to ensure privacy and public health value in consultation with local public health authorities sub_region_2 STRING Second geographic sub-region in which the data is aggregated. This varies by country/region to ensure privacy and public health value in consultation with local public health authorities metro_area STRING A specific metro area to measure mobility within a given city/metro area. This varies by country/region to ensure privacy and public health value in consultation with local public health authorities iso_3166_2_code STRING Unique identifier for the geographic region as defined by ISO Standard 3166-2. census_fips_code STRING Unique identifier for each US county as defined by the US Census Bureau. Maps to county_fips_code in other tables place_id STRING A textual identifier that uniquely identifies a place in the Google Places database and on Google Maps (details). For example ChIJd_Y0eVIvkIARuQyDN0F1LBA. For details see the following link: https://developers.google.com/places/web-service/place-id date DATE Changes for a given date as compared to baseline. Baseline is the median value for the corresponding day of the week during the 5-week period Jan 3–Feb 6 2020. retail_and_recreation_percent_change_from_baseline INT64 Mobility trends for places like restaurants cafes shopping centers theme parks museums libraries and movie theaters. grocery_and_pharmacy_percent_change_from_baseline INT64 Mobility trends for places like grocery markets food warehouses farmers markets specialty food shops drug stores and pharmacies. parks_percent_change_from_baseline INT64 Mobility trends for places like local parks national parks public beaches marinas dog parks plazas and public gardens. transit_stations_percent_change_from_baseline INT64 Mobility trends for places like public transport hubs such as subway bus and train stations. workplaces_percent_change_from_baseline INT64 Mobility trends for places of work. residential_percent_change_from_baseline INT64 Mobility trends for places of residence. source_url STRING Source etl_timestamp TIMESTAMP Load time for this data row

docs.title: covid19_jhu_csse
docs.text:
Description

Overview: This is the data repository for the 2019 Novel Coronavirus Visual Dashboard operated by the Johns Hopkins University Center for Systems Science and Engineering (JHU CSSE). This database was created in response to the Coronavirus public health emergency to track reported cases in real-time. The data include the location and number of confirmed COVID-19 cases, deaths and recoveries for all affected countries, aggregated at the appropriate province or state. It was developed to enable researchers, public health authorities and the general public to track the outbreak as it unfolds. Additional information is available in the blog post, Mapping 2019-nCoV (https://systems.jhu.edu/research/public-health/ncov/), and included data sources are listed here: https://github.com/CSSEGISandData/COVID-19

Dataset source: JHU CSSE

Update frequency: Daily

Terms of use: The contents of the dataset are provided to the public strictly for educational and academic purposes only. This data is from third party sources that may not be accurate, consistent and/or up-to-date. These datasets are provided “as is” without any warranties or representations of any kind. You are responsible for determining the suitability of this data for your purposes. See the JHU CSSE GitHub page for more details: https://github.com/CSSEGISandData/COVID-19

See the GCP Marketplace listing for more details, a full list of US boundary datasets, and sample queries: https://console.cloud.google.com/marketplace/details/johnshopkins/covid19_jhu_global_cases

docs.title: covid19_jhu_csse_eu
docs.text:
Description

Overview: This is the data repository for the 2019 Novel Coronavirus Visual Dashboard operated by the Johns Hopkins University Center for Systems Science and Engineering (JHU CSSE). This database was created in response to the Coronavirus public health emergency to track reported cases in real-time. The data include the location and number of confirmed COVID-19 cases, deaths and recoveries for all affected countries, aggregated at the appropriate province or state. It was developed to enable researchers, public health authorities and the general public to track the outbreak as it unfolds. Additional information is available in the blog post, Mapping 2019-nCoV (https://systems.jhu.edu/research/public-health/ncov/), and included data sources are listed here: https://github.com/CSSEGISandData/COVID-19

Dataset source: JHU CSSE

Update frequency: Daily

Terms of use: The contents of the dataset are provided to the public strictly for educational and academic purposes only. This data is from third party sources that may not be accurate, consistent and/or up-to-date. These datasets are provided “as is” without any warranties or representations of any kind. You are responsible for determining the suitability of this data for your purposes. See the JHU CSSE GitHub page for more details: https://github.com/CSSEGISandData/COVID-19

See the GCP Marketplace listing for more details, a full list of US boundary datasets, and sample queries: https://console.cloud.google.com/marketplace/details/johnshopkins/covid19_jhu_global_cases

docs.title: covid19_nyt
docs.text:
Description

Data on coronavirus cases and deaths in the U.S. published by The New York Times.

Sourced from https://github.com/nytimes/covid-19-data.

Tables

table infos excess_deathsLast update: As of Jan. 18, 2021, The New York Times are no longer updating this excess deaths dataset. We have updated data through the end of 2020 or as far as available. The New York Times is releasing data that documents the number of deaths from all causes that have occurred during the coronavirus pandemic for 32 countries. We are compiling this time series data from national and municipal health departments, vital statistics offices and other official sources in order to better understand the true toll of the pandemic and provide a record for researchers and the public. Official Covid-19 death tolls offer a limited view of the impact of the outbreak because they often exclude people who have not been tested and those who died at home. All-cause mortality is widely used by demographers and other researchers to understand the full impact of deadly events, including epidemics, wars and natural disasters. The totals in this data include deaths from Covid-19 as well as those from other causes, likely including people who could not be treated or did not seek treatment for other conditions. We have used this data to produce graphics tracking the oubreak's toll and stories about the United States, Ecuador, Russia, Turkey, Sweden and other countries. We would like to thank a number of demographers and other researchers, listed at the end, who have provided data or helped interpret it. Sourced from https://github.com/nytimes/covid-19-data/tree/master/excess-deaths. Last modified at: 2024-03-07Nb Rows: 7,258Size: 0.49 MBIs partitioned: TrueCreated at:2020-07-31 mask_use_by_countyThis data comes from a large number of interviews conducted online by the global data and survey firm Dynata at the request of The New York Times. The firm asked a question about mask use to obtain 250,000 survey responses between July 2 and July 14, enough data to provide estimates more detailed than the state level. (Several states have imposed new mask requirements since the completion of these interviews.) Specifically, each participant was asked: How often do you wear a mask in public when you expect to be within six feet of another person? This survey was conducted a single time, and at this point we have no plans to update the data or conduct the survey again. Sourced from https://github.com/nytimes/covid-19-data/tree/master/mask-use. Sourced from https://github.com/nytimes/covid-19-data. Description

Last update: As of Jan. 18, 2021, The New York Times are no longer updating this excess deaths dataset. We have updated data through the end of 2020 or as far as available. The New York Times is releasing data that documents the number of deaths from all causes that have occurred during the coronavirus pandemic for 32 countries. We are compiling this time series data from national and municipal health departments, vital statistics offices and other official sources in order to better understand the true toll of the pandemic and provide a record for researchers and the public. Official Covid-19 death tolls offer a limited view of the impact of the outbreak because they often exclude people who have not been tested and those who died at home. All-cause mortality is widely used by demographers and other researchers to understand the full impact of deadly events, including epidemics, wars and natural disasters. The totals in this data include deaths from Covid-19 as well as those from other causes, likely including people who could not be treated or did not seek treatment for other conditions. We have used this data to produce graphics tracking the oubreak's toll and stories about the United States, Ecuador, Russia, Turkey, Sweden and other countries. We would like to thank a number of demographers and other researchers, listed at the end, who have provided data or helped interpret it. Sourced from https://github.com/nytimes/covid-19-data/tree/master/excess-deaths.

docs.title: mask_use_by_county
docs.text:
Last modified at

2024-03-07

Created at

2020-07-31

Nb Rows

3,142

Size

0.14 MB

Description

This data comes from a large number of interviews conducted online by the global data and survey firm Dynata at the request of The New York Times. The firm asked a question about mask use to obtain 250,000 survey responses between July 2 and July 14, enough data to provide estimates more detailed than the state level. (Several states have imposed new mask requirements since the completion of these interviews.) Specifically, each participant was asked: How often do you wear a mask in public when you expect to be within six feet of another person? This survey was conducted a single time, and at this point we have no plans to update the data or conduct the survey again. Sourced from https://github.com/nytimes/covid-19-data/tree/master/mask-use.

Open in BigQuery 🡒

Columns

Column Type Description county_fips_code STRING Standard geographic identifier for the county never FLOAT64 The estimated share of people in this county who would say never in response to the question "How often do you wear a mask in public when you expect to be within six feet of another person?" rarely FLOAT64 The estimated share of people in this county who would say rarely sometimes FLOAT64 The estimated share of people in this county who would say sometimes frequently FLOAT64 The estimated share of people in this county who would say frequently always FLOAT64 The estimated share of people in this county who would say always

docs.title: covid19_symptom_search
docs.text:
Description

Terms of use To download or use the data, you must agree to the Google Terms of Service: https://policies.google.com/terms

Description The COVID-19 Search Trends symptoms dataset shows aggregated, anonymized trends in Google searches for a broad set of health symptoms, signs, and conditions. The dataset provides a daily or weekly time series for each region showing the relative volume of searches for each symptom.

This dataset is intended to help researchers to better understand the impact of COVID-19. It shouldn’t be used for medical diagnostic, prognostic, or treatment purposes. It also isn’t intended to be used for guidance on personal travel plans.

As of Dec. 15, 2020, the dataset was expanded to include trends for Australia, Ireland, New Zealand, Singapore, and the United Kingdom. This expanded data is available in new tables that provide data at country and two subregional levels. We are now producing aggregate weekly values computed from the individual daily values. To account for the newly available weekly-from-daily data, we adopted a new scaling factor for all US symptoms reported in the weekly time series. The method is described in the updated documentation linked below. We will not be updating existing state/county tables going forward.

To learn more about the dataset, how we generate it and preserve privacy, read the dataset documentation: https://storage.googleapis.com/gcp-public-data-symptom-search/COVID-19%20Search%20Trends%20symptoms%20dataset%20documentation%20.pdf

To visualize the data, try exploring these interactive charts and map of symptom search trends: https://pair-code.github.io/covid19_symptom_dataset

docs.title: covid19_usafacts
docs.text:
Description

Overview: This data from USAFacts (https://usafacts.org/visualizations/coronavirus-covid-19-spread-map/) provides US COVID-19 case and death counts by state and county. This data is sourced from the CDC, and state and local health agencies.

For more information, see the USAFacts site (https://usafacts.org/issues/coronavirus/) on the Coronavirus. Interactive data visualizations (https://usafacts.org/visualizations/coronavirus-covid-19-spread-map/) are also available via USAFacts.

Dataset source: USAFacts

Update frequency: Daily

Terms of use: The data are provided under the CC BY-SA 4.0 License (https://usafacts.org/terms-and-conditions/). The data are provided "AS IS" without any warranty, express or implied, from Google. Google disclaims all liability for any damages, direct or indirect, resulting from the use of the dataset.

docs.title: covid19_vaccination_search_insights
docs.text:
Description

Terms of use To download or use the data, you must agree to the Google Terms of Service: https://policies.google.com/terms

Description The COVID-19 Vaccination Search Insights data shows aggregated, anonymized trends in searches related to COVID-19 vaccination. The dataset provides a weekly time series for each region showing the relative interest of Google searches related to COVID-19 vaccination, across several categories.

The data is intended to help public health officials design, target, and evaluate public education campaigns.

To explore and download the data, use our interactive dashboard: http://goo.gle/covid19vaccinationinsights To learn more about the dataset, how we generate it and preserve privacy, read the data documentation: https://storage.googleapis.com/gcs-public-datasets/COVID-19%20Vaccination%20Search%20Insights%20documentation.pdf

Description

Terms of use To download or use the data, you must agree to the Google Terms of Service: https://policies.google.com/terms Description The COVID-19 Vaccination Search Insights data shows aggregated, anonymized trends in searches related to COVID-19 vaccination. The dataset provides a weekly time series for each region showing the relative interest of Google searches related to COVID-19 vaccination, across several categories. The data is intended to help public health officials design, target, and evaluate public education campaigns. To explore and download the data, use our interactive dashboard: http://goo.gle/covid19vaccinationinsights To learn more about the dataset, how we generate it and preserve privacy, read the data documentation: https://storage.googleapis.com/gcs-public-datasets/COVID-19%20Vaccination%20Search%20Insights%20documentation.pdf

Open in BigQuery 🡒

Columns

Column Type Description date DATE The first day of the week (starting on Monday) on which the searches took place. For example, in the weekly data the row labeled 2021-04-19 represents the search activity for the week of April 19 to April 25, 2021, inclusive. Calendar days start and end at midnight Pacific Standard Time. country_region STRING The name of the country in English. For example, United States. country_region_code STRING The ISO 3166-1 code for the country. For example, US. sub_region_1 STRING The name of a region in the country. For example, California. sub_region_1_code STRING A country-specific ISO 3166-2 code for the region. For example, US-CA. sub_region_2 STRING The name (or type) of a region in the country. Typically a subdivision of sub_region_1. For example, Santa Clara County or municipal_borough. sub_region_2_code STRING In the US, the FIPS code for a US county (or equivalent). For example, 06085. sub_region_3 STRING The name (or type) of a region in the country. Typically a subdivision of sub_region_2. For example, Downtown or postal_code. sub_region_3_code STRING In the US, the ZIP code. For example 94303. place_id STRING The Google place ID for the most-specific subregion. Used in the Google Places API and on Google Maps. For example, ChIJd_Y0eVIvkIARuQyDN0F1LBA. sni_covid19_vaccination FLOAT64 The scaled normalized interest related to all COVID-19 vaccination for the region and date. For example, 87.02. Empty when data isn't available. sni_vaccination_intent FLOAT64 The scaled normalized interest related to vaccination intent for the region and date. For example, 22.69. Empty when data isn't available. sni_safety_side_effects FLOAT64 The scaled normalized interest related to safety and side effects of the vaccines for the region and date. For example, 17.96. Empty when data isn't available.

Traces exported using Parity trace module https://wiki.parity.io/JSONRPC-trace-module.\nData is exported using https://github.com/medvedev1088/ethereum-etl\n

Open in BigQuery 🡒

Columns

Column Type Description transaction_hash STRING Transaction hash where this trace was in transaction_index INT64 Integer of the transactions index position in the block from_address STRING Address of the sender, null when trace_type is genesis or reward to_address STRING Address of the receiver if trace_type is call, address of new contract or null if trace_type is create, beneficiary address if trace_type is suicide, miner address if trace_type is reward, shareholder address if trace_type is genesis, WithdrawDAO address if trace_type is daofork value NUMERIC Value transferred in Wei input STRING The data sent along with the message call output STRING The output of the message call, bytecode of contract when trace_type is create trace_type STRING One of call, create, suicide, reward, genesis, daofork call_type STRING One of call, callcode, delegatecall, staticcall reward_type STRING One of block, uncle gas INT64 Gas provided with the message call gas_used INT64 Gas used by the message call subtraces INT64 Number of subtraces trace_address STRING Comma separated list of trace address in call tree error STRING Error if message call failed. This field doesn't contain top-level trace errors. status INT64 Either 1 (success) or 0 (failure, due to any operation that can cause the call itself or any top-level call to revert) block_timestamp TIMESTAMP Timestamp of the block where this trace was in block_number INT64 Block number where this trace was in block_hash STRING Hash of the block where this trace was in trace_id STRING Unique string that identifies the trace. For transaction-scoped traces it is {trace_type}{transaction_hash}. For block-scoped traces it is {trace_type}{block_number}

docs.title: transactions
docs.text:
Last modified at

2024-03-07

Created at

2019-01-15

Nb Rows

2,286,656,328

Size

1.95 TB

Description

Each block in the blockchain is composed of zero or more transactions. Each transaction has a source address, a target address, an amount of Ether transferred, and an array of input bytes. This table contains a set of all transactions from all blocks, and contains a block identifier to get associated block-specific information associated with each transaction. Data is exported using https://github.com/medvedev1088/ethereum-etl

Open in BigQuery 🡒

Columns

Column Type Description hash STRING Hash of the transaction nonce INT64 The number of transactions made by the sender prior to this one transaction_index INT64 Integer of the transactions index position in the block from_address STRING Address of the sender to_address STRING Address of the receiver. null when its a contract creation transaction value NUMERIC Value transferred in Wei gas INT64 Gas provided by the sender gas_price INT64 Gas price provided by the sender in Wei input STRING The data sent along with the transaction receipt_cumulative_gas_used INT64 The total amount of gas used when this transaction was executed in the block receipt_gas_used INT64 The amount of gas used by this specific transaction alone receipt_contract_address STRING The contract address created, if the transaction was a contract creation, otherwise null receipt_root STRING 32 bytes of post-transaction stateroot (pre Byzantium) receipt_status INT64 Either 1 (success) or 0 (failure) (post Byzantium) block_timestamp TIMESTAMP Timestamp of the block where this transaction was in block_number INT64 Block number where this transaction was in block_hash STRING Hash of the block where this transaction was in max_fee_per_gas INT64 Total fee that covers both base and priority fees max_priority_fee_per_gas INT64 Fee given to miners to incentivize them to include the transaction transaction_type INT64 Transaction type receipt_effective_gas_price INT64 The actual value per gas deducted from the senders account. Replacement of gas_price after EIP-1559

docs.title: crypto_kusama
docs.text:
Description

Polkadot enables interoperability among blockchains through its unique relay chain and parachain architecture. Kusama is a canary relay chain of Polkadot with separate parachains, typically used for higher risk and early stage projects, or to test new functionality before being deployed on Polkadot. Leading parachains include Moonriver (paraID 2023), Karura (paraID 2003), and Shiden (paraID 2007) and over 30 others, which like Polkadot+Kusama are built with Substrate. This dataset is an index of both the Kusama Relay Chain and most of its parachains, and is based on an index derived from Colorful Notion's Polkaholic.io, a multichain block explorer for the Polkadot+Kusama ecosystem.

Source listing: crypto_kusama

Column Type Description hash STRING Hash of the transaction nonce INT64 The number of transactions made by the sender prior to this one transaction_index INT64 Integer of the transactions index position in the block from_address STRING Address of the sender to_address STRING Address of the receiver. null when its a contract creation transaction value NUMERIC Value transferred in Wei gas INT64 Gas provided by the sender gas_price INT64 Gas price provided by the sender in Wei input STRING The data sent along with the transaction receipt_cumulative_gas_used INT64 The total amount of gas used when this transaction was executed in the block receipt_gas_used INT64 The amount of gas used by this specific transaction alone receipt_contract_address STRING The contract address created, if the transaction was a contract creation, otherwise null receipt_root STRING 32 bytes of post-transaction stateroot (pre Byzantium) receipt_status INT64 Either 1 (success) or 0 (failure) (post Byzantium) block_timestamp TIMESTAMP Timestamp of the block where this transaction was in block_number INT64 Block number where this transaction was in block_hash STRING EVM Hash of the block where this transaction was in max_fee_per_gas INT64 Total fee that covers both base and priority fees max_priority_fee_per_gas INT64 Fee given to miners to incentivize them to include the transaction transaction_type INT64 Transaction type receipt_effective_gas_price INT64 The actual value per gas deducted from the senders account. Replacement of gas_price after EIP-1559 fee FLOAT64 The actual transaction fee (in ether, 10^18) txn_saving FLOAT64 Total fee saved from the amount the user was willing to pay for this txn (in ether, 10^18) burned_fee FLOAT64 The amunt burned from this txn (in ether, 10^18) extrinsic_id STRING Identifier of the extrinsic extrinsic_hash STRING Blake2b Hash of the extrinsic method_id STRING The 4 byte hash of function signature signature STRING The inferred function signature, if available access_list JSON The accessList specifies a list of addresses and storage keys (introduced in EIP-2929) params JSON The decoded input, if available

spends inputs.spent_output_index INT64 The index of the output this input spends inputs.script_asm STRING Symbolic representation of the bitcoin's script language op-codes inputs.script_hex STRING Hexadecimal representation of the bitcoin's script language op-codes inputs.sequence INT64 A number intended to allow unconfirmed time-locked transactions to be updated before being finalized; not currently used except to disable locktime in a transaction inputs.required_signatures INT64 The number of signatures required to authorize the spent output inputs.type STRING The address type of the spent output inputs.addresses ARRAY<STRING> Addresses which own the spent output inputs.value NUMERIC The value in base currency attached to the spent output outputs.index INT64 0-indexed number of an output within a transaction used by a later transaction to refer to that specific output outputs.script_asm STRING Symbolic representation of the bitcoin's script language op-codes outputs.script_hex STRING Hexadecimal representation of the bitcoin's script language op-codes outputs.required_signatures INT64 The number of signatures required to authorize spending of this output outputs.type STRING The address type of the output outputs.addresses ARRAY<STRING> Addresses which own this output outputs.value NUMERIC The value in base currency attached to this output hash STRING The hash of this transaction size INT64 The size of this transaction in bytes virtual_size INT64 The virtual transaction size (differs from size for witness transactions) version INT64 Protocol version specified in block which contained this transaction lock_time INT64 Earliest time that miners can include the transaction in their hashing of the Merkle root to attach it in the latest block of the blockchain block_hash STRING Hash of the block which contains this transaction block_number INT64 Number of the block which contains this transaction block_timestamp TIMESTAMP Timestamp of the block which contains this transaction block_timestamp_month DATE Month of the block which contains this transaction input_count INT64 The number of inputs in the transaction output_count INT64 The number of outputs in the transaction input_value NUMERIC Total value of inputs in the transaction output_value NUMERIC Total value of outputs in the transaction is_coinbase BOOL true if this transaction is a coinbase transaction fee NUMERIC The fee paid by this transaction inputs ARRAY<STRUCT<index INT64, spent_transaction_hash STRING, spent_output_index INT64, script_asm STRING, script_hex STRING, sequence INT64, required_signatures INT64, type STRING, addresses ARRAY<STRING>, value NUMERIC>> Transaction inputs outputs ARRAY<STRUCT<index INT64, script_asm STRING, script_hex STRING, required_signatures INT64, type STRING, addresses ARRAY<STRING>, value NUMERIC>> Transaction outputs

docs.text:
Last modified at

2024-03-07

Created at

2023-10-30

Nb Rows

2,911,462

Size

535.48 MB

Description

Accounts data.

Open in BigQuery 🡒

Columns

Column Type Description _id STRING The address of the account, in bech32 encoding. Same as address. address STRING The address in bech32 encoding. Should be equal to the _id field. userName STRING The herotag the address possesses. balance STRING The EGLD balance, in atomic units. E.g. '1500000000000000000' means 1.5 EGLD. balanceNum FLOAT64 See balance. This value is expressed in EGLD. nonce FLOAT64 The sequence number of the address. shardID NUMERIC The shard of the account. timestamp TIMESTAMP The last moment when the address balance was changed. developerRewards STRING The developer rewards (for smart contract calls), in atomic units of EGLD. E.g. '1500000000000000000' means 1.5 EGLD. developerRewardsNum FLOAT64 See developerRewards. This value is expressed in EGLD. totalBalanceWithStake STRING Total balance of the account, including the staked amount, in atomic units of EGLD. E.g. '1500000000000000000' means 1.5 EGLD. totalBalanceWithStakeNum FLOAT64 See totalBalanceWithStake. This value is expressed in EGLD. currentOwner STRING The address in a bech32 format of the current owner of the smart contract. This field is populated only for the smart contract addresses. codeHash STRING The current code hash of the smart contract. rootHash STRING The root hash of the smart contract's data trie. codeMetadata STRING The code metadata of the smart contract.

Description

ESDTs of accounts.

Open in BigQuery 🡒

Columns

Column Type Description data.attributes STRING The attributes of the token. data.creator STRING The creator of the token (address). data.hash STRING Arbitrary field that should contain the hash of the NFT metadata. data.metadata STRING Token metadata. data.name STRING Token name. data.nonEmptyURIs BOOL Whether the token has non empty uris. data.whiteListedStorage BOOL Whether the token has whitelisted storage. An NFT/SFT has whitelisted storage if the URI belongs to one of the allowed decentralized storage services, such as IPFS or Pinata. data.royalties NUMERIC NFT royalties. Numeric value between 0 and 10000 (0 meaning 0% and 10000 meaning 100%). data.tags ARRAY<STRING> data.uris ARRAY<STRING> A list of URIs. _id STRING A unique identifier (opaque). address STRING The address in bech32 encoding. balance STRING The ESDT balance, in atomic units. balanceNum FLOAT64 See balance. currentOwner STRING data STRUCT<attributes STRING, creator STRING,hashSTRING, metadata STRING, name STRING, nonEmptyURIs BOOL, whiteListedStorage BOOL, royalties NUMERIC, tags ARRAY<STRING>, uris ARRAY<STRING>> A structure that contains additional information about a token. identifier STRING The extended identifier. E.g. TOKEN-01abdc-01. properties STRING shardID NUMERIC Shard of the account. timestamp TIMESTAMP The timestamp when the address balance was changed. token STRING The name of the token. tokenNonce FLOAT64 The sequence number of the token. This field is empty in the case of FungibleESDT. type STRING The type of the ESDT token. It can be FungibleESDT, NonFungibleESDT, SemiFungibleESDT, or MetaESDT. frozen BOOL Whether the tokens in question are 'frozen' for this account. paused BOOL Whether the token (collection) is 'paused'.

scheduledData.gasProvided FLOAT64 scheduledData.gasRefunded FLOAT64 scheduledData.penalized FLOAT64 scheduledData.rootHash STRING _id STRING The block hash. accumulatedFees STRING The accumulated fees that were payed in the block. developerFees STRING The developer fees that were accumulated in the block. epoch NUMERIC The epoch when the block was proposed and executed. epochStartBlock BOOL Whether the current block is an epoch-start block. epochStartInfo STRUCT<nodePrice STRING, prevEpochStartHash STRING, prevEpochStartRound NUMERIC, rewardsForProtocolSustainability STRING, rewardsPerBlock STRING, totalNewlyMinted STRING, totalSupply STRING, totalToDistribute STRING> A structure with information about the new epoch. epochStartShardsData ARRAY<STRUCT<epoch NUMERIC, firstPendingMetaBlock STRING, headerHash STRING, lastFinishedMetaBlock STRING, nonce NUMERIC, pendingMiniBlockHeaders ARRAY<STRUCT<hashSTRING, receiverShard NUMERIC, senderShard NUMERIC, timestamp TIMESTAMP, type STRING>>, rootHash STRING, round NUMERIC, scheduledRootHash STRING, shardID NUMERIC>> An array of structures with information about the epoch start. gasPenalized FLOAT64 The total gas that was penalized in the block. gasProvided FLOAT64 The total gas that was provided in the block. gasRefunded FLOAT64 The total gas that was refunded in the block. maxGasLimit FLOAT64 The total gas that can be provided in the block. miniBlocksDetails ARRAY<STRUCT<firstProcessedTx NUMERIC, lastProcessedTx NUMERIC, senderShard NUMERIC, receiverShard NUMERIC, mbIndex NUMERIC, type STRING, procType STRING, txsHashes ARRAY<STRING>, executionOrderTxsIndices ARRAY<NUMERIC>>> An array of structures with information about the miniblocks within the block. miniBlocksHashes ARRAY<STRING> An array of the miniblock hashes (hexadecimal encoded) that were included in the block. nonce NUMERIC The sequence number of the block (block height). notarizedBlocksHashes ARRAY<STRING> The hashes of the blocks that were notarized in the current block. notarizedTxsCount NUMERIC The number of transactions that were notarized in the block. prevHash STRING The hash of the previous block. proposer NUMERIC The index of the validator that proposed the block. pubKeyBitmap STRING The pub key bitmap. round NUMERIC The round when the block was proposed and executed. scheduledData STRUCT<accumulatedFees STRING, developerFees STRING, gasProvided FLOAT64, gasRefunded FLOAT64, penalized FLOAT64, rootHash STRING> A structure that contains data about the scheduled execution. searchOrder NUMERIC shardId NUMERIC The shard this block belongs to. size NUMERIC The size of the block in bytes. sizeTxs NUMERIC The size of the block's transactions in bytes. stateRootHash STRING The trie's state root hash when the block was proposed and executed. timestamp TIMESTAMP The timestamp when the block was proposed and executed. txCount NUMERIC The number of transactions that were executed in the block. validators ARRAY<NUMERIC> An array that contains the indices of the validators that signed the block. signature STRING The block signature. leaderSignature STRING The leader signature. randSeed STRING The random seed. prevRandSeed STRING The random seed of the previous block. receiptsHash STRING The receipts hash. softwareVersion STRING The software version. chainID STRING The chain ID.

Description

Operations (transactions and transactions results).

Columns

Column Type Description _id STRING The transaction or smart contract result hash. callType STRING Call type (for smart contract results). canBeIgnored BOOL code STRING The contract code (for smart contract deployments and upgrades). data STRING Additional information for a transaction. It can contain a simple message, a function call, an ESDT transfer payload, and so on. esdtValues ARRAY<STRING> A list of ESDT values that are transferred. Values are expressed in atomic units. fee STRING The amount of EGLD the sender paid for the transaction, expressed in atomic units. feeNum FLOAT64 See fee field. function STRING The name of the function that is called in case of a smart contract call. gasLimit FLOAT64 The maximum gas units the sender is willing to pay for. gasPrice FLOAT64 The amount to be paid for each gas unit. gasUsed FLOAT64 The amount of gas used by the transaction. hasOperations BOOL Whether the transaction has smart contract results. hasScResults BOOL Whether the transaction has smart contract results. hasLogs BOOL Whether the transaction has event logs. initialPaidFee STRING The initial amount of EGLD the sender paid for the transaction, before the refund. isRelayed BOOL Whether the transaction is a relayed transaction. isScCall BOOL Whether the transaction is a smart contract call. miniBlockHash STRING The hash of the miniblock in which the transaction was included. nonce NUMERIC The transaction sequence number of the sender. operation STRING The operation of the transaction, given the data field. originalSender STRING The sender of the original transaction. originalTxHash STRING The hash of the original transaction. prevTxHash STRING The hash of the previous transaction (for smart contract results). receiver STRING The receiver address. receiverShard NUMERIC The shard of the receiver address. receivers ARRAY<STRING> A list of receiver addresses (one element for now). receiversShardIDs ARRAY<NUMERIC> A list of receiver addresses shard IDs (one element for now). receiverUserName STRING The username of the receiver address. relayedValue STRING relayerAddr STRING The address of the relayer. returnMessage STRING The return message (for smart contract calls). round NUMERIC The round of the block when the transaction was executed. searchOrder NUMERIC sender STRING The address of the transaction sender. senderShard NUMERIC The shard of the sender address. senderUserName STRING The username of the sender address. signature STRING The signature of the transaction, hex-encoded. status STRING The status of the transaction. timestamp TIMESTAMP The timestamp of the block in which the transaction was executed. tokens ARRAY<STRING> A list of ESDT tokens that are transferred by the transaction. type STRING The operation type: normal in case of a user-signed transaction and unsigned in case of a smart contract result. value STRING The amount of EGLD transferred, in atomic units. E.g. '1500000000000000000' means 1.5 EGLD. version NUMERIC The version (for normal transactions). valueNum FLOAT64 See value field. This value is expressed in EGLD. esdtValuesNum ARRAY<FLOAT64> See esdtValues field. guardian STRING The guardian address, if the sender has a guardian. guardianSignature STRING The signature of the guardian. errorEvent BOOL Whether the transaction has an event that indicates an error. completedEvent BOOL Whether the transaction has an event that indicates completion.

E.g. '1500000000000000000' means 1.5 EGLD. valueNum FLOAT64 See value field. This value is expressed in EGLD. esdtValuesNum ARRAY<FLOAT64> See esdtValues field.

Description

NEAR is a user-friendly and carbon-neutral blockchain, built from the ground up to be performant, secure, and infinitely scalable. In technical terms, NEAR is a layer one, sharded, proof-of-stake blockchain built with usability in mind. In simple terms, NEAR is blockchain for everyone.

docs.title: crypto_polkadot
docs.text:
Description

Polkadot enables interoperability among blockchains through its unique relay chain and parachain architecture. Leading parachains include Moonbeam, Astar, Nodle, Acala, and over 30 others, which like Polkadot are built with Substrate.

This dataset is an index of both the Polkadot Relay Chain and most of its parachains, and is based on an index derived from Colorful Notion's Polkaholic.io, a multichain block explorer for the Polkadot ecosystem.

Source listing: crypto_polkadot

The Polygon blockchain is composed of a series of blocks. This table contains a set of all blocks in the blockchain and their attributes.\nData is exported using https://github.com/blockchain-etl/polygon-etl

Open in BigQuery 🡒

Columns

Column Type Description timestamp TIMESTAMP The timestamp for when the block was collated number INT64 The block number hash STRING Hash of the block parent_hash STRING Hash of the parent block nonce STRING Hash of the generated proof-of-work sha3_uncles STRING SHA3 of the uncles data in the block logs_bloom STRING The bloom filter for the logs of the block transactions_root STRING The root of the transaction trie of the block state_root STRING The root of the final state trie of the block receipts_root STRING The root of the receipts trie of the block miner STRING The address of the beneficiary to whom the mining rewards were given difficulty NUMERIC Integer of the difficulty for this block total_difficulty NUMERIC Integer of the total difficulty of the chain until this block size INT64 The size of this block in bytes extra_data STRING The extra data field of this block gas_limit INT64 The maximum gas allowed in this block gas_used INT64 The total used gas by all transactions in this block transaction_count INT64 The number of transactions in the block base_fee_per_gas INT64 Protocol base fee per gas, which can move up or down

Description

The most popular type of transaction on the Polygon blockchain invokes a contract of type ERC20 to perform a transfer operation, moving some number of tokens from one 20-byte address to another 20-byte address. This table contains the subset of those transactions and has further processed and denormalized the data to make it easier to consume for analysis of token transfer events. Data is exported using https://github.com/blockchain-etl/polygon-etl

Open in BigQuery 🡒

Columns

Column Type Description token_address STRING ERC20 token address from_address STRING Address of the sender to_address STRING Address of the receiver value STRING Amount of tokens transferred (ERC20) / id of the token transferred (ERC721). Use safe_cast for casting to NUMERIC or FLOAT64 transaction_hash STRING Transaction hash log_index INT64 Log index in the transaction receipt block_timestamp TIMESTAMP Timestamp of the block where this transfer was in block_number INT64 Block number where this transfer was in block_hash STRING Hash of the block where this transfer was in

For transaction-scoped traces it is {trace_type}{transaction_hash}. docs.title: transactions
docs.text:
Last modified at

2024-03-07

Created at

2023-12-07

Nb Rows

3,698,177,733

Size

4.56 TB

Description

Each block in the blockchain is composed of zero or more transactions. Each transaction has a source address, a target address, an amount of Matic transferred, and an array of input bytes. This table contains a set of all transactions from all blocks, and contains a block identifier to get associated block-specific information associated with each transaction. Data is exported using https://github.com/blockchain-etl/polygon-etl

Open in BigQuery 🡒

Columns

Column Type Description hash STRING Hash of the transaction nonce INT64 The number of transactions made by the sender prior to this one transaction_index INT64 Integer of the transactions index position in the block from_address STRING Address of the sender to_address STRING Address of the receiver. null when its a contract creation transaction value NUMERIC Value transferred in Wei gas INT64 Gas provided by the sender gas_price INT64 Gas price provided by the sender in Wei input STRING The data sent along with the transaction receipt_cumulative_gas_used INT64 The total amount of gas used when this transaction was executed in the block receipt_gas_used INT64 The amount of gas used by this specific transaction alone receipt_contract_address STRING The contract address created, if the transaction was a contract creation, otherwise null receipt_root STRING 32 bytes of post-transaction stateroot (pre Byzantium) receipt_status INT64 Either 1 (success) or 0 (failure) (post Byzantium) block_timestamp TIMESTAMP Timestamp of the block where this transaction was in block_number INT64 Block number where this transaction was in block_hash STRING Hash of the block where this transaction was in max_fee_per_gas INT64 Total fee that covers both base and priority fees max_priority_fee_per_gas INT64 Fee given to miners to incentivize them to include the transaction transaction_type INT64 Transaction type. One of 0 (Legacy), 1 (Legacy), 2 (EIP-1559) receipt_effective_gas_price INT64 The actual value per gas deducted from the senders account. Replacement of gas_price after EIP-1559

docs.title: Advisories
docs.text:
Last modified at

2024-03-03

Created at

2022-05-12

Nb Rows

1,758,606

Size

1.82 GB

Description

This table stores information about security advisories related to packages from any of npm, Go, Maven, PyPI and Cargo. Each row represents a single advisory and can be identified by Source and SourceID.

Open in BigQuery 🡒

Columns

Column Type Description Packages.System STRING The system of the affected package Packages.Name STRING The name of the affected package Packages.AffectedVersions STRING The versions of the package affected by the advisory Packages.UnaffectedVersions STRING The versions of the package unaffected by the advisory SnapshotAt TIMESTAMP When this row was exported. Source STRING The upstream source of this advisory, example values include 'GHSA', 'NSWG' and 'OSV'. SourceID STRING The id of this advisory within its upstream source. SourceURL STRING A link to this advisory in its upstream source. Title STRING Brief human-readable description of the advisory. Description STRING A description of the advisory. ReferenceURLs ARRAY<STRING> URLs that elaborate on an advisory: longer descriptions, corroborating evidence, patches, issue trackers, release notes and so on. CVSS3Score NUMERIC(3, 1) A numeric measure of severity according to the CVSS3 spec. The measure ranges from 0-10 and is to 1 decimal place. Severity STRING A discrete scale of the severity, derived from the CVSS3Score. Example values include 'NONE', 'LOW', 'MEDIUM', 'HIGH', 'CRITICAL', 'UNKNOWN'. GitHubSeverity STRING The severity of this advisory as determined by GitHub. Example values include 'LOW', 'MODERATE', 'HIGH', 'CRITICAL', 'UNKNOWN'. Disclosed TIMESTAMP The time at which this advisory was publicly disclosed. Packages ARRAY<STRUCT<System STRING, Name STRING, AffectedVersions STRING, UnaffectedVersions STRING>> An array of the packages affected by this advisory. Aliases ARRAY<STRING> Other identifiers used for the advisory, including CVEs.

Description

This table stores information about specific versions of packages. Each row represents a single version of a package.

Columns

Column Type Description Links.Label STRING A label for the corresponding URL value. Example values include 'DOCUMENTATION', 'ISSUE_TRACKER', 'HOMEPAGE' and 'SOURCE_REPO'. Links.URL STRING The URL value. Advisories.Source STRING The upstream source of this advisory, example values include 'OSV', 'GHSA' and 'NSWG'. Advisories.SourceID STRING The id of this advisory within its upstream source. VersionInfo.IsRelease BOOL The value is true if the version is considered a release, as opposed to a pre-release. VersionInfo.Ordinal INT64 The value allows the versions of a package to be sorted in semantic order without parsing the version string. If a package has its versions sorted in ascending order by VersionInfo.Ordinal, the order will correspond to the order of the version strings as determined by the package management system. Hashes.Type STRING The type of hash, example values include 'SHA512' and 'SHA1'. Hashes.Hash STRING A base64 encoded string of the hash. SLSAProvenance.SourceRepository STRING The source code repository used to build this version. SLSAProvenance.Commit STRING The commit of the source code repository the version was built from. SLSAProvenance.URL STRING The URL of the provenance statement. SLSAProvenance.Verified BOOL The Sigstore bundle containing this attestation was verified using the sigstore-go library. SnapshotAt TIMESTAMP When this row was exported. System STRING The dependency management system of the package-version. Name STRING The name of the package-version. Version STRING The version of the package-version. Licenses ARRAY<STRING> An array of the licenses used by this package-version, presented as SPDX expressions. Links ARRAY<STRUCT<Label STRING, URL STRING>> An array of links related to this package-version, each consisting of a Label and URL. Advisories ARRAY<STRUCT<Source STRING, SourceID STRING>> An array of Advisories that affect this package-version directly. This can be used to join against the Advisories table. VersionInfo STRUCT<IsRelease BOOL, Ordinal INT64> Information extracted from the string value in the Version column of this row. Hashes ARRAY<STRUCT<Type STRING,HashSTRING>> An array of hashes that have been observed from this package-version. DependenciesProcessed BOOL True if this version's dependency requirements have been processed. DependencyError BOOL True if an error was encountered while processing this version's dependency requirements. UpstreamPublishedAt TIMESTAMP The time at which this package-version was published, as reported by the upstream source. Registries ARRAY<STRING> An array of the package management registries this package-version is available from. Description

Columns

Column Type Description state_code STRING The FIPS code of the state in which the monitor resides. county_code STRING The FIPS code of the county in which the monitor resides. site_num STRING A unique number within the county identifying the site. parameter_code INT64 The AQS code corresponding to the parameter measured by the monitor. poc INT64 This is the “Parameter Occurrence Code” used to distinguish different instruments that measure the same parameter at the same site. latitude FLOAT64 The monitoring site’s angular distance north of the equator measured in decimal degrees. longitude FLOAT64 The monitoring site’s angular distance east of the prime meridian measured in decimal degrees. datum STRING The Datum associated with the Latitude and Longitude measures. parameter_name STRING The name or description assigned in AQS to the parameter measured by the monitor. Parameters may be pollutants or non-pollutants. sample_duration STRING The length of time that air passes through the monitoring device before it is analyzed (measured). So, it represents an averaging period in the atmosphere (for example, a 24-hour sample duration draws ambient air over a collection filter for 24 straight hours). For continuous monitors, it can represent an averaging time of many samples (for example, a 1-hour value may be the average of four one-minute samples collected during each quarter of the hour). pollutant_standard STRING A description of the ambient air quality standard rules used to aggregate statistics. (See description at beginning of document.) date_local DATE The calendar date for the summary. All daily summaries are for the local standard day (midnight to midnight) at the monitor. units_of_measure STRING The unit of measure for the parameter. QAD always returns data in the standard units for the parameter. Submitters are allowed to report data in any unit and EPA converts to a standard unit so that we may use the data in calculations. event_type STRING Indicates whether data measured during exceptional events are included in the summary. A wildfire is an example of an exceptional event; it is something that affects air quality, but the local agency has no control over. No Events means no events occurred. Events Included means events occurred and the data from them is included in the summary. Events Excluded means that events occurred but data form them is excluded from the summary. Concurred Events Excluded means that events occurred but only EPA concurred exclusions are removed from the summary. If an event occurred for the parameter in question, the data will have multiple records for each monitor. observation_count INT64 The number of observations (samples) taken during the day. observation_percent FLOAT64 The percent representing the number of observations taken with respect to the number scheduled to be taken during the day. This is only calculated for monitors where measurements are required (e.g., only certain parameters). arithmetic_mean FLOAT64 The average (arithmetic mean) value for the day. first_max_value FLOAT64 The highest value for the day. first_max_hour INT64 The hour (on a 24-hour clock) when the highest value for the day (the previous field) was taken. aqi INT64 The Air Quality Index for the day for the pollutant, if applicable. method_code INT64 An internal system code indicating the method (processes, equipment, and protocols) used in gathering and measuring the sample. The method name is in the next column. method_name STRING A short description of the processes, equipment, and protocols used in gathering and measuring the sample. local_site_name STRING The name of the site (if any) given by the State, local, or tribal air pollution control agency that operates it. address STRING The approximate street address of the monitoring site. state_name STRING The name of the state where the monitoring site is located. county_name STRING The name of the county where the monitoring site is located. city_name STRING The name of the city where the monitoring site is located. This represents the legal incorporated boundaries of cities and not urban areas. cbsa_name STRING The name of the core bases statistical area (metropolitan area) where the monitoring site is located. date_of_last_change DATE The date the last time any numeric values in this record were updated in the AQS data system.

Columns

Column Type Description classification STRING Numerical designation (I, II, or III) that is assigned by FDA to a particular product recall that indicates the relative degree of health hazard. Class I = Dangerous or defective products that predictably could cause serious health problems or death. Examples include: food found to contain botulinum toxin, food with undeclared allergens, a label mix-up on a lifesaving drug, or a defective artificial heart valve. Class II = Products that might cause a temporary health problem, or pose only a slight threat of a serious nature. Example: a drug that is under-strength but that is not used to treat life-threatening situations. Class III = Products that are unlikely to cause any adverse health reaction, but that violate FDA labeling or manufacturing laws. Examples include: a minor container defect and lack of English labeling in a retail food. center_classification_date DATE report_date DATE Date that the FDA issued the enforcement report for the product recall. postal_code STRING termination_date DATE recall_initiation_date DATE Date that the firm first began notifying the public or their consignees of the recall. recall_number STRING A numerical designation assigned by FDA to a specific recall event used for tracking purposes. city STRING The city in which the recalling firm is located. more_code_info STRING event_id INT64 A numerical designation assigned by FDA to a specific recall event used for tracking purposes. distribution_pattern STRING General area of initial distribution such as, “Distributors in 6 states: NY, VA, TX, GA, FL and MA; the Virgin Islands; Canada and Japan”. The term “nationwide” is defined to mean the fifty states or a significant portion. Note that subsequent distribution by the consignees to other parties may not be included. openfda_application_number STRING This corresponds to the NDA, ANDA, or BLA number reported by the labeler for products which have the corresponding Marketing Category designated. If the designated Marketing Category is OTC Monograph Final or OTC Monograph Not Final, then the application number will be the CFR citation corresponding to the appropriate Monograph (e.g. “part 341”). For unapproved drugs, this field will be null. openfda_brand_name STRING The brand or trade name of the product. openfda_dosage_form STRING The dosage form of the drug product. openfda_generic_name STRING The dosage form of the drug product. openfda_manufacturer_name STRING Name of company corresponding to the labeler code segment of the NDC. openfda_product_ndc STRING The labeler manufacturer code and product code segments of the NDC number, separated by a hyphen. openfda_product_type STRING The route of administration of the drug product. openfda_route STRING The type of drug product. openfda_substance_name STRING The list of active ingredients of a drug product. openfda_spl_id STRING A unique identifier for a particular version of a Structured Product Label for a product. Also referred to as the document ID. openfda_spl_set_id STRING A unique identifier for the Structured Product Label for a product, which is stable across versions of the label. openfda_pharm_class_moa STRING Mechanism of action. Molecular, subcellular, or cellular level functional activity of a drug product’s pharmacologic class. openfda_pharm_class_cs STRING Chemical structure. Chemical structure classification of a pharmacologic class. openfda_pharm_class_pe STRING Physiologic effect. Tissue, organ, or organ system level functional activity of a pharmacologic class. openfda_pharm_class_epc STRING Established pharmacologic class. A pharmacologic class associated with an approved indication of an active moiety that the FDA has determined to be scientifically valid and clinically meaningful. openfda_upc STRING Documentation forthcoming. openfda_unii STRING The Unique Ingredient Identifier of the drug or substance. openfda_rxcui STRING The RxNorm Concept Unique Identifier. RxCUI is a unique number that describes a semantic concept about the drug product, including its ingredients, strength, and dosage forms. recalling_firm STRING The firm that initiates a recall or, in the case of an FDA requested recall or FDA mandated recall, the firm that has primary responsibility for the manufacture and (or) marketing of the product to be recalled. voluntary_mandated STRING Describes who initiated the recall. Recalls are almost always voluntary, meaning initiated by a firm. A recall is deemed voluntary when the firm voluntarily removes or corrects marketed products or the FDA requests the marketed products be removed or corrected. A recall is mandated when the firm was ordered by the FDA to remove or correct the marketed products, under section 518(e) of the FD&C Act, National Childhood Vaccine Injury Act of 1986, 21 CFR 1271.440, Infant Formula Act of 1980 and its 1986 amendments, or the Food Safety Modernization Act (FSMA). state STRING The U.S. state in which the recalling firm is located. reason_for_recall STRING Information describing how the product is defective and violates the FD&C Act or related statutes. initial_firm_notification STRING The method(s) by which the firm initially notified the public or their consignees of a recall. A consignee is a person or firm named in a bill of lading to whom or to whose order the product has or will be delivered. status STRING On-Going = A recall which is currently in progress. Completed = The recall action reaches the point at which the firm has actually retrieved and impounded all outstanding product that could reasonably be expected to be recovered, or has completed all product corrections. Terminated = FDA has determined that all reasonable efforts have been made to remove or correct the violative product in accordance with the recall strategy, and proper disposition has been made according to the degree of hazard. Pending = Actions that have been determined to be recalls, but that remain in the process of being classified. product_type STRING country STRING The country in which the recalling firm is located. product_description STRING Brief description of the product being recalled. code_info STRING A list of all lot and/or serial numbers, product numbers, packer or manufacturer numbers, sell or use by dates, etc., which appear on the product or its labeling. address_1 STRING address_2 STRING product_quantity STRING The amount of defective product subject to recall.

Class I = Dangerous or defective products that predictably could cause serious health problems or death. Examples include: food found to contain botulinum toxin, food with undeclared allergens, a label mix-up on a lifesaving drug, or a defective artificial heart valve. Example: a drug that is under-strength but that is not used to treat life-threatening situations. docs.title: fec
docs.text:
Description

The FEC dataset contains committee, candidate and campaign finance data for the current election cycle and for election cycles through 1980.

Specifically the data set contains the following data points:

Committees(CM Data Dictionary): The committee tables contains one record for each committee registered with the Federal Election Commission. This includes federal political action committees and party committees, campaign committees for presidential, house and senate candidates, as well as groups or organizations who are spending money for or against candidates for federal office.

Candidates(CN Data Dictionary): The candidate tables contains one record for each candidate who has either registered with the Federal Election Commission or appeared on a ballot list prepared by a state elections office.

Candidate-Committee Linkages(CCL Data Dictionary): These tables contains one record for each candidate to committee linkage.

Itemized Records (Any Transaction from One Committee to Another)(OTH Data Dictionary): The itemized records (miscellaneous transactions) tables contains all transactions (contributions, transfers, etc. among federal committees). Contributions to Candidates(PAS2 Data Dictionary) : These tables are a subset of the Itemized Records (OTH) tables. The itemized committee contributions file contains each contribution or independent expenditure made by a PAC, party committee, candidate committee, or other federal committee to a candidate during the two-year election cycle.

Individual Contributions(INDIV Data Dictionary) : The individual contributions file contains each contribution from an individual to a federal committee.

Operating Expenditures(OPPEXP Data Dictionary) : The Operating Expenditures file contains disbursements reported on FEC Form 3 Line 17, FEC Form 3P Line 23and FEC Form 3X Lines 21(a)(i), 21(a)(ii) and 21(b)

Source: http://classic.fec.gov/finance/disclosure/ftpdet.shtml

docs.title: ghcn_d
docs.text:
Description

Overview: NOAA’s Global Historical Climatology Network (GHCN) is an integrated database of climate summaries from land surface stations across the globe that have been subjected to a common suite of quality assurance reviews. The data are obtained from more than 20 sources. The GHCN-Daily is an integrated database of daily climate summaries from land surface stations across the globe, and is comprised of daily climate records from over 100,000 stations in 180 countries and territories, and includes some data from every year since 1763.

Update frequency: Daily

Dataset source: NOAA

Terms of use: This dataset is publicly available for anyone to use under the following terms provided by the Dataset Source — http://www.data.gov/privacy-policy#data_policy — and is provided "AS IS" without any warranty, express or implied, from Google. docs.title: ghcn_m
docs.text:
Description

Overview: NOAA’s Global Historical Climatology Network (GHCN) is an integrated database of climate summaries from land surface stations across the globe that have been subjected to a common suite of quality assurance reviews. The data are obtained from more than 20 sources. The GHCN-Monthly is a temperature dataset that contains monthly mean temperatures and is used for operational climate monitoring activities. It is comprised of climate records from over 7,000 stations.

Update frequency: Daily

Dataset source: NOAA

Terms of use: This dataset is publicly available for anyone to use under the following terms provided by the Dataset Source — http://www.data.gov/privacy-policy#data_policy — and is provided "AS IS" without any warranty, express or implied, from Google. Columns

Column Type Description id INT64 11 digit identifier, digits 1-3=Country Code, digits 4-8 represent the WMO id if the station is a WMO station. It is a WMO station if digits 9-11="000". latitude FLOAT64 latitude of station in decimal degrees longitude FLOAT64 longitude of station in decimal degrees stnelev STRING the station elevation in meters. -999.0 = missing. name STRING station name grelev INT64 station elevation in meters estimated from gridded digital terrain data popcls STRING population class (U=Urban (>50,000 persons); (S=Suburban (>=10,000 and <= 50,000 persons); (R=Rural (<10,000 persons) popsiz INT64 the population of the city or town the station is location in (expressed in thousands of persons). topo STRING type of topography in the environment surrounding the station, (Flat-FL,Hilly-HI,Mountain Top-MT,Mountainous Valley-MV). stveg STRING type of vegetation in environment of station if station is Rural and when it is indicated on the Operational Navigation Chart (Desert-DE,Forested-FO,Ice-IC,Marsh-MA). stloc STRING indicates whether station is near lake or ocean (<= 30 km of ocean-CO, adjacent to a lake at least 25 square km-LA). ocndis INT64 distance to nearest ocean/lake from station (km). airstn STRING airport station indicator (A=station at an airport). towndis INT64 distance from airport to center of associated city or town (km). grveg STRING vegetation type at nearest 0.5 deg x 0.5 deg gridded data point of vegetation dataset (44 total classifications). popcss STRING population class as determined by Satellite night lights (C=Urban, B=Suburban, A=Rural)

docs.title: google_cloud_release_notes
docs.text:
Description

This dataset contains release notes for the majority of generally available Google Cloud products found on cloud.google.com. You can use this BigQuery public dataset to consume release notes programmatically across all products. HTML versions of release notes are available within each product's documentation and also in a filterable format at https://console.cloud.google.com/release-notes. Note: The release notes in this dataset are delayed a few days compared to the HTML versions.

docs.title: google_political_ads
docs.text:
Description

Overview: This dataset contains information on how much money is spent by verified advertisers on political advertising across Google Ad Services. In addition, insights on demographic targeting used in political ad campaigns by these advertisers are also provided. Finally, links to the actual political ad in the Google Transparency Report (https://adstransparency.google.com) are provided. Data for an election expires 7 years after the election. After this point, the data are removed from the dataset and are no longer available.

Update frequency: Daily

Dataset source: Transparency Report: Political Advertising on Google

Terms of use:

See the GCP Marketplace listing for more details and sample queries: https://console.cloud.google.com/marketplace/details/transparency-report/google-political-ads

For more information see: The Political Advertising on Google Transparency Report at https://adstransparency.google.com

The supporting Frequently Asked Questions at https://support.google.com/transparencyreport/answer/9575640?hl=en&ref_topic=7295796

Tables

table infos advertiser_declared_statsCertain California and New Zealand advertisers are required to submit additional data about themselves. The advertiser is responsible for the accuracy of this information, which Google has not confirmed. For California, this information is provided from our express notification process required for certain California advertisers, which is separate from our verification process. Description

Certain California and New Zealand advertisers are required to submit additional data about themselves. The advertiser is responsible for the accuracy of this information, which Google has not confirmed. For California, this information is provided from our express notification process required for certain California advertisers, which is separate from our verification process. For New Zealand, this information is provided during our verification process.

Open in BigQuery 🡒

Column Type Description advertiser_id STRING ID of the advertiser who purchased the ad. region STRING Advertiser region. advertiser_declared_name STRING The advertiser's committee declared name. advertiser_declared_regulatory_id STRING Committee declared identification number. advertiser_declared_scope STRING Committee-provided information about the candidate and office or ballot proposition and jurisdiction to which the advertisement refers which is separate from our verification process. advertiser_declared_promoter_name STRING The New Zealand advertiser's declared Promoter Statement name. advertiser_declared_promoter_address STRING The New Zealand advertiser's declared Promoter Statement address.

docs.title: iowa_liquor_sales
docs.text:
Description

"This dataset contains every wholesale purchase of liquor in the State of Iowa by retailers for sale to individuals since January 1, 2012. The State of Iowa controls the wholesale distribution of liquor intended for retail sale (off-premises consumption), which means this dataset offers a complete view of retail liquor consumption in the entire state. The dataset contains every wholesale order of liquor by all grocery stores, liquor stores, convenience stores, etc., with details about the store and location, the exact liquor brand and size, and the number of bottles ordered. You can find more details, as well as sample queries, in the GCP Marketplace here: https://console.cloud.google.com/marketplace/details/iowa-department-of-commerce/iowa-liquor-sales"

This provides a unique identifier for the individual liquor products included in the store order. date DATE Date of order store_number STRING Unique number assigned to the store who ordered the liquor. store_name STRING Name of store who ordered the liquor. address STRING Address of store who ordered the liquor. city STRING City where the store who ordered the liquor is located zip_code STRING Zip code where the store who ordered the liquor is located store_location GEOGRAPHY Location of store who ordered the liquor. The Address, City, State and Zip Code are geocoded to provide geographic coordinates. Accuracy of geocoding is dependent on how well the address is interpreted and the completeness of the reference data used. county_number STRING Iowa county number for the county where store who ordered the liquor is located county STRING County where the store who ordered the liquor is located category STRING Category code associated with the liquor ordered category_name STRING Category of the liquor ordered. vendor_number STRING The vendor number of the company for the brand of liquor ordered vendor_name STRING The vendor name of the company for the brand of liquor ordered item_number STRING Item number for the individual liquor product ordered. item_description STRING Description of the individual liquor product ordered. pack INT64 The number of bottles in a case for the liquor ordered bottle_volume_ml INT64 Volume of each liquor bottle ordered in milliliters. state_bottle_cost FLOAT64 The amount that Alcoholic Beverages Division paid for each bottle of liquor ordered state_bottle_retail FLOAT64 The amount the store paid for each bottle of liquor ordered bottles_sold INT64 The number of bottles of liquor ordered by the store sale_dollars FLOAT64 Total cost of liquor order (number of bottles multiplied by the state bottle retail) volume_sold_liters FLOAT64 Total volume of liquor ordered in liters. (i.e. (Bottle Volume (ml) x Bottles Sold)/1,000)" volume_sold_gallons FLOAT64 Total volume of liquor ordered in gallons. (i.e. (Bottle Volume (ml) x Bottles Sold)/3785.411784)"

docs.title: libraries_io
docs.text:
Description

Libraries.io gathers data on open source software from 33 package managers and 3 source code repositories. We track over 2.4m unique open source projects, 25m repositories and 121m interdependencies between them. This gives Libraries.io a unique understanding of open source software.

In this release you will find data about software distributed and/or crafted publicly on the Internet. You will find information about its development, its distribution and its relationship with other software included as a dependency.

You will not find any information about the individuals who create and maintain these projects.

https://libraries.io/data

Attribution: Includes data from Libraries.io Digital Object identifier: 10.5281/zenodo.1196312.

Column Type Description id INT64 The unique primary key of the project in the Libraries.io database. platform STRING The name of the Package manager the project is available on. name STRING The name of the project, unique by Platform (case sensitive). created_timestamp TIMESTAMP The timestamp of when Libraries.io first discovered the project. updated_timestamp TIMESTAMP The timestamp of when Libraries.io last saved a change to the project. description STRING Description provided by the package manager, falling back to description from repository if empty. keywords STRING Comma separated array of keywords if supported by package manager. homepage_url STRING URL of webpage or repository as provided by package managers that support it. licenses STRING Comma separated array of SPDX identifiers for licenses declared in package manager meta data or submitted manually by Libraries.io user via "project suggection" feature. repository_url STRING URL of source code repository declared in package manager metadata or submitted manually by Libraries.io user via "project suggection" feature. versions_count INT64 Number of published versions of the project found by Libraries.io. sourcerank INT64 Libraries.io defined score based on quality, popularity and community metrics. latest_release_publish_timestamp TIMESTAMP Time of the latest release detected by Libraries.io (ordered by semver, falling back to publish date for invalid semver). latest_release_number STRING Version number of the latest release detected by Libraries.io (ordered by semver, falling back to publish date for invalid semver). package_manager_id INT64 Unique ID of project from package manager API, only currently used by PlatformIO. dependent_projects_count INT64 Number of other projects that declare the project as a dependency in one or more of their versions. language STRING Primary programming language the project is written in, pulled from the repository if source is hosted on GitHub. status STRING Either Active, Deprecated, Unmaintained, Help Wanted, Removed, no value also means active. Updated when detected by Libraries.io or submitted manually by Libraries.io user via "project suggection" feature. last_synced_timestamp TIMESTAMP Timestamp of when Libraries.io last synced the project from it's package manager API. dependent_repositories_count INT64 The total count of open source repositories that list the project as a dependency as detected by Libraries.io. repository_id INT64 The unique primary key of the repository for this project in the Libraries.io database.
